<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Resumption of Framework Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reaction to Resumption of Framework Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Framework Priorities Agreed </H4>

<F P=102> OW2605095394 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 May 
94 Evening Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2605095394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Japan-U.S. Economic Framework Talks are set to 
resume, but Japan is already facing more problems because the 
United States wants to add five additional areas, including 
"banking services" to the list of priority issues to be 
addressed at the talks. 
  Japan faced a tough enough time at the talks settling the 
question of objective criteria in the existing agreed three 
priority, including automobiles and auto parts. The additions 
mean Japan faces difficult negotiations over more areas. 
  If the "deregulation and competitive policy" is included, it 
will probably have an impact on the outline of exterior economic 
policy reform, which the government planned to finish by the end 
of June. 
  Japan says it will discuss the issue of expanding the 
priority list with the United States, but it is expected to 
basically accept the U.S. request. "Banking services" and 
"deregulation and competitive policy" had been the subject of 
bilateral negotiations up until February, when the whole 
framework talks broke down. But because so little progress was 
made, the Japanese Government feels "this is a new start." 
  The "deregulation and competitive policy" area is expected 
to 
command a lot of attention and the Japanese Government is at 
present working on details to be included in the outline of the 
exterior economic policy reform. If Japan-U.S. negotiations on 
this area begin, it is possible that the U.S. demands on 
deregulation will be clearly visible in the outline. 
  Japan is very concerned about the fact that sheet glass and 
forestry products have been raised as areas for negotiation. 
Each is an area in which certain U.S. companies and pressure 
groups have been putting pressure on the U.S. Government. If 
Japan is slow to act, the United States may take sanctions under 
Section 301 of the 1988 Omnibus Trade Act. 
  In the informal negotiations on resuming the framework 
talks, 
the United States may appear to have made a concession by 
retracting its demand for numerical targets. However, its 
demand that additional trade areas be discussed can be seen as a 
new way of shaking up Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

