<H3> <TI>   Talks Start With PRC on GATT Membership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Talks Start With PRC on GATT Membership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2505125894 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 May 
94 Morning Edition p 9 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2505125894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Hiroyuki Akita] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 24 May -- Japan and China started the 
first two-day negotiation meeting in Beijing on 23 May to talk 
abut the possibility of China becoming a member of GATT. As a 
condition for China to Join the GATT, Japan had called for a 
reduction of tariff rates on 3,300 industrial goods and China 
gave answers on 2,800 items. However, it seems that both 
countries need more time before reaching an agreement because, 
"there still exists a big gap" between their proposals 
(according to the Japanese negotiation team). 
  It will be the first full-fledged negotiation meeting 
between 
the two countries regarding China's joining GATT. 

</TEXT>

