<H3> <TI>   Inspection Method for Nuclear Testing Proposed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Inspection Method for Nuclear Testing Proposed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005132894 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 20 May 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2005132894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Yoshiaki Ito] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, 19 May -- During a working group session of 
the Geneva disarmament conference on 19 May, under which 
negotiations on concluding a treaty on comprehensive test ban 
are in progress, the Japanese Government presented a proposal 
that will be the basis for the draft accord. The proposal 
incorporates a nuclear inspection system consisting of the three 
on-site inspection methods -- seismological inspection method, a 
method to inspect radioactive fallout, and an international 
inspection method -- as means to inspect nuclear tests conducted 
secretly. 
  At the working session, Yoshitomo Tanaka, ambassador 
accredited to the Geneva disarmament conference, announced for 
the first time that a comprehensive inspection system should be 
established after coordinating and incorporating each nation's 
own inspection methods into Japan-proposed system. He then 
asked the member nations to conclude negotiations by the time 
Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT) is extended next April. 

</TEXT>

