<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Council Urges Positive Approach in Security Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Council Urges Positive Approach in Security Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2705081194 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 May 
94 Evening Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2705081194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The "Defense Policy Council" (chaired by Asahi 
Breweries Ltd. Chairman Hirotaro Higuchi), a private advisory 
body to Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata, held a meeting at the prime 
minister's official residence on the morning of 25 May, and 
exchanged views on the international situation after the end of 
the Cold War. It was confirmed that "it is necessary to prevent 
regional disputes and proliferation of mass destruction arms 
because there are isolated and unpredictable dangers in various 
places." Taking such a situation into consideration, the 
council agreed that "Japan should take positive actions to 
resolve international problems," and decided to make this view 
the framework of a report to be submitted to the prime minister. 
  With regard to the Asian and Pacific situation, the 
participants cited the following as important issues: 1) while 
the economy in this region is steadily developing, its security 
system is immature; 2) interests of the major military powers, 
such as the United States, Russia, and China, are entangled. 
The council decided to state in the report its view that 
Japan's defense capability "will become an increasingly 
important component for the security environment of the Asian 
and Pacific region." 

</TEXT>

