<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Considering Reconnaissance Satellites </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Considering Reconnaissance Satellites </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2705031094 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 27 
May 94 </F>



<TEXT>
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY 
<F P=103> OW2705031094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 27 May Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata commented on the issue 
of Japan's acquiring reconnaissance satellites at the House of 
Representatives Budget Committee on 26 May. He said, "It is 
time to consider how far this can be done for information 
gathering, and to think of what to do," in response to a 
question from Wataru Hiraizumi (Liberal Democratic Party). This 
remark of the prime minister, which indicated he does not 
discount such a possibility, is bound to trigger a debate in 
relation to an existing Diet resolution on the "peaceful use of 
outer space." 
  Hiraizumi interpellated Hata on security issues in relation 
with the situation on the Korean peninsula. He asked if Japan 
should acquire reconnaissance satellites to strengthen its 
capability to gather and analyze information. Hata responded, 
"It is important to possess accurate information to ensure 
security. However, satellites have to do with flying over other 
countries' territories, which is a controversial question. That 
is why there has been little progress." This indicated that the 
issue is indeed being examined. 
  At present, for analytical purposes, Japan purchases from 
the 
United States photographs taken by meteorological satellites. 
However, such photographs have much lower definition than 
photographs from reconnaissance satellites. For this reason, 
officials of the Defense Agency have been asking for Japan's own 
reconnaissance satellites. 
  However, the Foreign Ministry is concerned about the impact 
of this on neighboring countries. The United States is also 
asking Japan to participate in the Theater Missile Defense (TMD) 
program. Some ministry officials are of the opinion that owning 
such satellites "is not good for Japan-U.S. economic relations." 
  In May 1969, the Diet adopted a resolution stipulating that 
"objects launched into outer space, and rockets use for 
launching should be used only for peaceful purposes." 

</TEXT>

