<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aid Requested for Aluminum Industry in Indonesia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aid Requested for Aluminum Industry in Indonesia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1805191294 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 13 May 
94 Morning Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1805191294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] The Indonesian Government has asked the Ministry 
of International Trade and Industry [MITI) to extend financial 
assistance to Asahan [name as published] Aluminum, a state-run 
aluminum smelting company in which Japanese firms have a stake. 
The financial assistance being sought by the Indonesian 
Government is that: 1) Japan's Overseas Economic Cooperation 
Fund and Japanese firms that invest in Asahan Aluminum subscribe 
for about 10 billion worth of shares in a fresh capital increase 
to be made by Asahan Aluminum; and 2) the current interest rate 
on approximately 190 billion yen in loans extended by the Export 
and Import Bank of Japan be lowered. Asahan Aluminum has come 
into being as the sole overseas aluminum production base for 
Japanese firms that have withdrawn from their overseas aluminum 
smelting business, and the Japanese firms have staked their 
survival on the aluminum smelting industry in Indonesia. 
Nonetheless, Asahan Aluminum has continued to register a poor 
performance because of sluggish aluminum markets around the 
world. MITI plans to accept in principle the Indonesian 
Government's request for the financial assistance after 
concluding that Japan needs to secure an overseas source of 
aluminum ingots to prepare itself for potential fluctuations of 
the world aluminum market. MITI will discuss specific ways to 
provide the financial assistance with 12 Japanese firms, 
including the Sumimoto Chemical Company and the Nippon Light 
Metal Company, which have invested in Asahan Aluminum, and the 
Finance Ministry and the Export and Import Bank of Japan. 
[passage omitted on the establishment of Asahan Aluminum] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

