<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iranian Transport Official Discusses Debts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Iranian Transport Official Discusses Debts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2704082994 Sofia BTA in English 1722 GMT 26 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2704082994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, April 26 (BTA) -- Mr. Valentin Karabashev, 
deputy prime minister and minister of trade, today received Mr. 
'Ali Akbar Torkan, Iran's minister of roads and transport, the 
government Press Office told BTA. Mr. Torkan is visiting here 
at the head of an Iranian delegation for the 9th session of the 
Bulgarian-Iranian Commission for Economic, Scientific and 
Technological Cooperation which opened yesterday [25 April]. 
  The two ministers focused on bilateral trade and payments. 
The guest emphasized that Iran has problems in repaying its 
debt to Bulgaria in hard currency. Mr. Torkan suggested 
repayment in oil, gas and industrial goods of a value equal to 
Iran's obligations to Bulgaria. 
  Mr. Karabashev stressed that the finances of most of Iran's 
Bulgarian creditors are now in a rather bad state. They will 
count on getting their money back from Iran in hard currency. 
  Later in the day, Mr. Torkan was also received by Deputy 
Prime Minister Evgeni Matinchev. Mr. Matinchev was briefed on 
the results of the 9th session of the Bulgarian-Iranian 
Commission for Economic, Scientific and Technological 
Cooperation. The guest reiterated Iran's desire to repay its 
debt to Bulgaria in industrial goods and oil. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

