<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bulgaria's Daskalov Arrives, Meets Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bulgaria's Daskalov Arrives, Meets Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Havel Receives Documents on 1968 </H4>

<F P=102> AU2904091494 Prague CTK in English 1923 GMT 28 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2904091494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 28 (CTK) -- Documents from archives 
of the Bulgarian Foreign, Interior, and Defense Ministries 
concerning the invasion of Czechoslovakia by Warsaw Pact troops 
in 1968 were handed over to Czech President Vaclav Havel today 
by Bulgarian Foreign Minister Stanislav Daskalov. Daskalov told 
journalists after the meeting that the documents contained 
primarily an assessment of the events which preceded the 
military invasion and followed it by "former Bulgarian and 
Czechoslovak functionaries." 
  Havel said that today's act followed his earlier talks with 
Bulgarian President Zhelyu Zhelev at which Havel showed interest 
in such documents. Part of the "national hygiene" is to know 
better one's own country's history, Havel said, adding that he 
would extend the documents to a commission of historians dealing 
with the 1968 events. 
  Daskalov pointed out that the Bulgarian Parliament had in 
1990 officially apologized to the former Czechoslovakia for 
Bulgaria's role in the events. Asked why Bulgaria was handing 
over the documents concerning 1968 only now Daskalov said that 
it was probably because in Bulgaria is more bureaucracy. 
  Havel said that his meeting with Daskalov today served as an 
opportunity for exchanging information on the current political 
situation in both countries and on prospects for mutual 
relations. He said he believed there were no political problems 
or contested issues between the Czech Republic and Bulgaria. 
The two countries hold similar views on many questions and 
orientate their foreign policy in the same direction, he added. 
  Hungary was the first country to hand over documents 
concerning the 1968 events to the former Czechoslovakia in June 
1990, six days after Czechoslovak archive documents concerning 
the 1956 Hungarian revolution were handed over to Hungary. 
  In August 1991, Czechoslovakia officially asked the former 
Soviet Union for access to the Soviet Government and party 
archives. In December 1991, Soviet Ambassador to Czechoslovakia 
Aleksandr Lebedev handed over documents concerning the events of 
1968 and 1969 to Vojtech Mencl, chairman of the Czechoslovak 
governmental commission looking into the period. The documents 
contained reports which were sent by the then Soviet ambassador 
to Czechoslovakia to Moscow and the orders from Moscow. 
  Russian President Boris Yeltsin handed over two packages of 
archive materials to the then Czechoslovak President Havel 
during his visit to Moscow in April 1992. The materials came 
predominantly from the archives of the former Soviet Communist 
Party and from the KGB. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-54406 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu083__a94020" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-083-A </AU>
