<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kocarnik, Schmognerova Differ on Old Claims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kocarnik, Schmognerova Differ on Old Claims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2804110994 Prague CTK in English 0724 GMT 28 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2804110994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague April 28 (CTK) -- Czech Finance Minister 
Ivan Kocarnik said last night he did not share Slovakia's 
optimism that the old bloc claims and liabilities between the 
Czech Republic and Slovakia were far lower than estimated by the 
Czech Industry and Trade Ministry. Speaking to journalists after 
his return from the spring session of the International Monetary 
Fund (IMF) and the World Bank, he was reacting to a statement 
made by Slovak Deputy Premier Brigita Schmognerova made during 
their meeting in Washington. 
  Schmognerova indicated that the method of settling the 
"old-bloc claims" had "still to be considered," Kocarnik said. 
He added that Schmognerova, however, did not say how the 
government wanted to solve the situation. 
  On Tuesday [26 April] Kocarnik told CTK in Washington that 
the Czech and Slovak Governments had agreed on March 25 to 
convert the liabilities into ECUs using the exchange rate in 
effect before the currency split. The claims would be 
transferred to the new bloc and the old would be abolished, he 
added. Under the old bloc, the 1-1 ratio is applied for 
payments related to trade deals concluded before the currency 
split on February 8, 1993. The new bloc uses ECUs. 
  Kocarnik also pointed out that the Czech Government had 
approved an amendment to the Czech-Slovak payments agreement to 
this effect two weeks ago. He stressed last night that it was 
in Slovakia's interest that a settlement reached as soon as 
possible because Slovakia was the loser. Both parties agreed it 
was now necessary to verify the volume of old claims and 
liabilities, he added. 
  Kocarnik pointed out that until September Slovakia's steps 
would be influenced by the elections slated to take place on 
September 30- October 1. It will therefore be difficult to 
distinguish between economic rationality and election-motivated 
politics. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

