<H3> <TI>   Principles of Administrative Reform Approved </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Principles of Administrative Reform Approved </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2704191494 Prague CTK in English 1632 GMT 27 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2704191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 27 (CTK) -- At its meeting today, the 
Czech Government discussed and approved the principles for a 
constitutional bill on higher self-administrative units to be 
submitted to Parliament by April 30, Premier Vaclav Klaus told 
journalists. 
  He said the government had thoroughly reworked and regrouped 
the materials. The first part concerns general powers of higher 
administrative units while the second one defines which powers 
would be transferred to higher administrative units from central 
bodies, Klaus said. The third part specifies areas where the 
higher units would have the right to set up institutions. These 
would include social care, education, health care, transport, 
culture, and the environment, he said. 
  Klaus said that the approved principles would "facilitate 
the 
next stage of the work on the future administrative arrangement 
of the state." 

</TEXT>

