<H3> <TI>   Ministries Clash Over Mining Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministries Clash Over Mining Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2804201294 Prague CTK in English 1640 GMT 28 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2804201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 28 (CTK) -- Czech Environment 
Minister Frantisek Benda told journalists today that his 
ministry might submit its own mining bill which would put an 
emphasis on environmental protection. He said the Environment 
Ministry's idea of the bill differed considerably from that of 
the Ministry of the Economy. Both ministries had been charged 
with the joint preparation of the principles for the bill. 
  At the beginning of the year Benda pointed out that the 
Environment Ministry would seek to include all important aspects 
concerning the protection of the mining environment in the 
initial bill drawn up by the Economy Ministry. He said today 
that the two bills have just joined together, whereas he had 
expected that a single bill would be drafted. A completely 
unacceptable situation arose in which about "ten diametrically 
opposed views" stand against each other. 
  Disputes between the ministries concerned, for example, the 
definition of public interest which had been defined very 
liberally and on a low level as regards the protection of 
owners' rights or the protection of the environment or mining 
site, Benda said. The two ministries are using the same words 
but their notions are different, he said. 

</TEXT>

