<H3> <TI>   Communist Party Calls For Early Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Communist Party Calls For Early Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2804164894 Prague CTK in English 1227 GMT 28 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2804164894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 28 (CTK) -- The time has come to 
demand early parliamentary elections, since the results of the 
last elections (held in June 1992) are, according to the 
Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia (KSCM), steadily being 
challenged, KSCM Deputy Chairman Zdenek Klanica told journalists 
today. 
  The KSCM believes that after modification by the 
parliamentary budgetary committee, the draft amendment to the 
law on political parties, which is now being discussed in 
parliament, entirely ignores the results of the June 1992 
elections. KSCM Chairman Miroslav Grebenicek said that the 
ruling right-wing parties, along with some opposition parties, 
wanted the amendment to weaken mainly the KSCM. "Those who 
support the amendment in its present form, will be well paid by 
right-wing parties for their accommodating move," Grebenicek 
added. 
  Vojtech Filip, a KSCM expert on legislation, criticized the 
efforts to ban political parties from running any businesses, 
and described them as attempts to impair the "constitutional 
equality of all forms of property". Parties should be allowed 
to at least edit and publish, Filip said. 
  He added he was convinced that the aim of the discussed 
amendment was mainly to restrict funding of the KSCM and weaken 
it in the forthcoming local and Senate elections. 
  Grebenicek said that in the elections, the KSCM would be 
also 
paralyzed by a ban on editing activities, as it would cause it 
difficulties with the printing of advertisements during the 
pre-election campaign. In contrast to this, the right-wing 
parties would remain intact, as they "have a considerable 
majority of the media at their disposal, and their 
representatives have enough financial opportunities to publish 
any documents," Grebenicek said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

