<H3> <TI>   Fidesz Rejects Liberal-Socialist Coalition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fidesz Rejects Liberal-Socialist Coalition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2704092094 Budapest MTI in English 1930 GMT 26 Apr 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2704092094 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 26 April (MTI) -- According to the 
chairman of the Federation of Young Democrats (Fidesz), Viktor 
Orban, there will be no coalition agreement between the 
Hungarian Socialist Party (MSZP) and the Alliance of Free 
Democrats (SZDSZ), and all guesses of this kind are provocations 
by the MSZP. Orban made the remarks at a rally held in Budapest 
on Tuesday [26 April]. 
  The Fidesz chairman's firm position is interesting in light 
of the fact that numerous conjectures have appeared in press in 
the past weeks, whereby the liberal SZDSZ and the Socialists 
would reach agreement and enter into coalition. As four liberal 
parties -- Fidesz, SZDSZ, Agrarian Federation, and 
Entrepreneurs' Party -- have already formed an election 
alliance, a possible agreement between the SZDSZ and the MSZP 
would question this agreement. 
  Reacting to the guesses so far, several Fidesz leaders have 
firmly stated they are not willing to cooperate with the MSZP. 
"In order for the SZDSZ to agree with the MSZP, they would have 
to betray us first," Orban said. 
  According to Orban, the MSZP is not in the favorable 
position 
it presents itself to be. He predicted that the alleged 
advantage of the MSZP will further dwindle in the remaining 
period of the election campaign. 

</TEXT>

