<F P=102>   AU2804192894 Budapest MTI in English 1529 GMT 28 Apr 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2804192894 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 28 April (MTI) -- After tough internal 
squabbles, the Democratic Hungarian Community of Vojvodina 
(VMDK) has been consolidated, with its realistic line winning a 
two-thirds majority, VMDK president Andras Agoston announced in 
Budapest on Thursday [28 April] after meeting government 
representatives and party officials. Cross-Border Hungarians 
Office President Geza Entz said their talks covered a proposal 
for ethnic Hungarian organizations to receive certain 
contribution to their budgets. 
  Agoston said the VMDK's re-elected leadership maintains its 
demand for autonomy, and has already talked unofficially to 
Serbia's prime minister. Settling the position of Hungarians in 
Vojvodina is closely connected with international circumstances. 
"An agreement with Serbia will work if it also serves Serb 
interests," he added. 
  He quoted President Clinton's special emissary's call for 
autonomy for Croatian Serbs and Albanians in rump Yugoslavia. 
With a precedent for ethnic minority autonomy, Hungarians in 
Vojvodina would have more chance for their own demands, Agoston 
said. 

</TEXT>

