<H3> <TI>   Jeszenszky on Minorities, Ties With Neighbors </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jeszenszky on Minorities, Ties With Neighbors </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2904110694 Budapest MTI in English 2027 GMT 28 Apr 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2904110694 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 28 April (MTI) -- Hungarian Foreign 
Minister Geza Jeszenszky at a Hungarian Democratic Forum (MDF) 
election rally in Budapest's Obuda district on Thursday evening 
[28 April], said that the MDF had said in 1989 that Hungary 
wanted to return to the European road, and had asked for the 
world's support. "Experience shows that although Hungary does 
get help from the West, we have to adapt mainly on our own," 
Jeszenszky said. 
  Jeszenszky said Hungary fosters excellent relations with 
four 
of its neighbors: Austria, Slovenia, Croatia, and Ukraine. 
With good political relations, the rights of minorities are 
also regulated by exemplary contracts. 
  Links with three other states -- Slovakia, Romania, and 
Serbia -- are not satisfactory. In this context, Jeszenszky 
said Hungarian diplomacy encourages democratic rights for the 
Hungarian national minorities living in those countries, in line 
with European principles. 

</TEXT>

