<H3> <TI>   Rosati Not To Seek Ministerial Posts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rosati Not To Seek Ministerial Posts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2604150494 Warsaw PAP in English 1446 GMT 26 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2604150494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, April 26 -- Dariusz Rosati, the ruling 
coalition's candidate for the post of deputy prime minister and 
finance minister, on Tuesday resigned from seeking the posts. 
Rosati was to have filled the posts after his predecessor, 
Marek Borowski resigned a few weeks ago, but President Lech 
Walesa refused to accept him. 
  In a letter addressed to Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak and 
leader of the Democratic Left Alliance (SLD) Aleksander 
Kwasniewski Rosati wrote that "another candidate should be 
sought urgently, one that would win support of the coalition and 
the president." 
  Rosati firmly rejected the arguments raised against his 
candidature by "the president and his representatives," but is 
of the opinion that the course of political developments in 
Poland over the past month indicates ever more clearly that the 
coalition is unable to persuade Walesa to approve him as a 
candidate for the posts of deputy prime minister and finance 
minister. Efficient performance of these functions would be 
"very difficult in the conditions of a lack of approval on the 
part of the Belvedere." 
  Rosati thinks that it is in the interest of the country to 
urgently seek another candidate for the vacant posts. 
"Energetic actions to this end are necessary in face of ever 
more visible symptoms that the economic and social situation in 
the country is getting destabilised," Rosati wrote. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

