<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Ministers Comment on Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Ministers Comment on Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0205095394 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 0500 GMT 2 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0205095394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 0500 GMT 2 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Gregor Martin Papucsek from </F>
Budapest] 
  [Excerpts] Last night's dialogue between the Slovak and 
Hungarian prime ministers was not in vain. At least they 
established which of the problems were of greater importance. 
One of these problems is the so-called basic treaty, which 
contains a clause on the unalterability of the border. This is 
what Peter Boross said when responding to my question about 
whether the Hungarian side allowed itself be convinced by Jozef 
Moravcik's arguments: 
  [Begin Boross recording, in Hungarian with superimposed 
translation into Slovak] Given the complexity of this issue and 
the type of talks we have had, we were unable to reach a final 
agreement. This, of course, does not counter our intention to 
examine all the issues, systematically and as a part of a 
consistent dialogue. But that requires a lot of time. We must 
adopt a realistic attitude when solving difficult issues. [end 
recording] 
  Since we want to adopt a realistic attitude, the first thing 
we could agree on is the opening of new border crossings. True, 
the prime ministers failed both to define specific crossings and 
to set specific dates. But the Slovak side does not link this 
issue with the readmission agreement, as was the case until the 
recent past. Slovak Prime Minister Jozef Moravcik said: 
  [Begin Moravcik recording] We discussed the readmission 
agreement (?before). We do not link the conclusion of this 
agreement with border crossings. We indicated the ways in which 
existing differences in views on both sides can be overcome. 
There is a need for more talks with other states, so that the 
stream of people coming from other countries, particularly from 
Germany, would not be halted in either country. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

