<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crvenkovski: Balkans on `Brink of a New War' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crvenkovski: Balkans on `Brink of a New War' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA3004160494 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1505 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA3004160494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Skopje, April 30 (AA) -- Macedonian Prime Minister 
Branko Crvenkovski on Saturday said that the Balkans are under a 
war threat, warning that Greece and Serbia are aiming at 
creating a joint border after disintegrating Macedonia [The 
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM]. 
  "Neither country is willing to accept the reality of an 
independent Macedonia in the Balkans. Both have common 
interests in Macedonia," he said. 
  Speaking to AA reporters in Skopje, he accused the European 
Union and United Nations of following "a passive policy in the 
region", adding this indecisive attitude by international 
organizations has brought the region on the brink of a new war. 
  Crvenkovski said there is a great political harmony between 
Belgrade and Athens, stressing the greatest support for Serbia 
comes from Athens and that the embargo imposed on his country by 
Greece was started with cooperation with Serbia. 
  He said Turkey is Macedonia's "best friend" in the Balkans, 
expressing gratitude for its support. "Turkey's policy is one 
that Macedonia is looking for and expects," he concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-54463 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu084_m_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-084 </AU>
