<H3> <TI>   Ganic Condemns World's `Failure To Act' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ganic Condemns World's `Failure To Act' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0105142994 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 1 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0105142994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] The main European and world ceremony celebrating 
international labor day on 1 May, was held in Sarajevo today. 
The secretary generals of the three largest trade union 
confederations in Europe and the world visited Sarajevo today 
for the occasion. [passage omitted] 
  [Unidentified correspondent] Ejup Ganic, member of the 
Bosnian presidency, also addressed the meeting on behalf of 
President Izetbegovic and the Bosnia-Herzegovina presidency. 
  [Begin Ganic recording] It is not by accident that the 
world's largest trade union confederations have chosen Sarajevo 
as the venue for this year's main May Day celebration. This 
reveals a bad conscience because the world has failed to do all 
that it can for Bosnia-Herzegovina. Workers, those who are 
least to blame for the failure to act, are doing this to catch 
the attention of UN politicians, politicians of all countries, 
people who hold the power. In the name of human solidarity, in 
the name of the moral and political principles they uphold, they 
should not have left a country of hard-working people, a country 
of culture, science, and work, to the tender mercies of the 
armed chetnik gangs. What is all the more humiliating is that 
this country and its people have been denied the right to defend 
themselves by the imposition of an unjust embargo on the import 
of arms. 
  The so-called protected area of Gorazde was defended by the 
courage of almost unarmed defenders who sustained the assaults 
by the aggressors equipped with (state-of-the-art) weapons of 
mass destruction. Those who prevented a more effective defense 
and protection of Gorazde and its residents are the accomplices 
of the crime in that town. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

