<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNPROFOR Reports Attack </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNPROFOR Reports Attack </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0205061394 Paris AFP in English 2311 GMT 1 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0205061394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, May 2 (AFP) -- Three shells exploded here 
Sunday in apparent violation of a ceasefire and a heavy weapons 
ban, the United Nations said. Two shells fell about 300 metres 
(yards) east of the Grbavica bridge, which links the downtown 
Serb-held district with the rest of the city that is controlled 
by the Moslem-dominated government army, according to Guy Vinet, 
a UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR) officer. A third shell was 
later reported falling on the outskirts of the city. There were 
no immediate reports of injuries and Eric Chaperon, UNPROFOR 
spokesman, described the shelling as part of the usual 
cease-fire violations. Government and Serb forces, faced with a 
threat of NATO airstrikes, were ordered in February to place all 
heavy weapons under UN control or move them outside a 
20-kilometre (12-mile) exclusion zone. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-54485 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu084_i_94022" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-084 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   One Killed, Three Wounded in Tuzla Shelling </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    One Killed, Three Wounded in Tuzla Shelling </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0105203894 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2000 GMT 1 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0105203894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] The chetniks today showed us yet again in the 
most brutal way that, as far as they were concerned, no UN 
decisions on protected areas in Bosnia-Herzegovina had any 
validity. Between 1500 and 1600 GMT this afternoon they fired 
several artillery shells on Tuzla. This attack against civilian 
targets caused fresh casualties: One 22-year-old girl was 
killed, one person seriously, and three lightly wounded. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

